# Extraction: Two major Hebrew love-concepts identifiable in the scholarly literature

---

## Concept 1: אַהֲבָה / אָהַב (ʾahavah / ʾahav)

| Field | Extraction |
|---------|---------|
| Tradition | Hebrew (Biblical Hebrew) |
| Love concept | אַהֲבָה / אָהַב (ʾahavah / ʾahav) |
| Core claim | ʾAhav/ʾahavah functions as a relational bond that can describe divine-human, political-covenantal, familial, and romantic attachment. |
| Mechanism | *CONTESTED.* Ackerman argues that covenantal and interpersonal uses share a hierarchical structure in which the superior party is frequently characterized as the lover. Cash argues that Deuteronomic love combines affective, behavioral, political, and attachment dimensions. |
| Cost | *CONTESTED.* In covenantal contexts, love entails loyalty and obligation within an asymmetrical relationship; scholars disagree whether the emphasis is primarily affective, political, behavioral, or attachment-based. |
| Protection target | Israel–YHWH covenant relationship; also family and intimate human relationships depending on textual context. |
| Contested? | **Yes.** Major dispute concerns whether biblical ʾahav should be understood primarily as emotion, covenant loyalty, political allegiance, attachment behavior, or some combination thereof. |

### Cross-tradition lineage flag

Potential antecedent to later Judeo-Christian formulations associated with agapē. Coordinate with Greek extraction to avoid double-counting lineage effects.

