## Concept 2: חֶסֶד (ḥesed)

| Field | Extraction |
|---------|---------|
| Tradition | Hebrew (Biblical Hebrew) |
| Love concept | חֶסֶד (ḥesed) |
| Core claim | Ḥesed denotes covenantal loyalty expressed through concrete acts of faithfulness, kindness, mercy, or steadfast commitment within a relationship. |
| Mechanism | Relationship → obligation/faithfulness → action. Scholarship consistently describes ḥesed as enacted rather than merely felt; it operates through maintaining obligations and trust within an established relationship or covenant. |
| Cost | The actor bears obligations of loyalty, assistance, and continued faithfulness even under adverse conditions. In Ruth, scholars argue that acts of ḥesed are often costly survival strategies within restrictive social structures. |
| Protection target | Covenant relationships, vulnerable persons within those relationships, and the continuity of communal trust. |
| Contested? | **Yes.** Scholars disagree whether ḥesed is best translated as love, mercy, kindness, loyalty, covenant faithfulness, grace, or some irreducible combination of these. Debate concerns translation and semantic center rather than its relational character. |

### Cross-tradition lineage flag

Frequently identified as part of the Hebrew covenantal tradition that informs later Jewish and Christian conceptions of divine love, including traditions later expressed through agapē discourse.

