# Flags (G4 ambiguity log)

## FLAG 1 — Hebrew scholarship does not yield a clean set of discrete love-types

Unlike the Greek extraction, Hebrew scholarship generally centers on lexical fields (especially ʾahav and ḥesed) whose meanings vary across divine, political, familial, and romantic contexts. The literature does not consistently partition love into separate categories analogous to erōs/philia/agapē/storgē.

## FLAG 2 — ʾAHAV is heavily contested

Recent scholarship explicitly describes love in Deuteronomy as affective, behavioral, and political simultaneously. No consensus operational mechanism was identified. Any single-mechanism extraction would violate G4.

## FLAG 3 — ḤESED translation remains disputed

The scholarly dispute is not whether ḥesed exists as a coherent concept, but what English gloss best captures it: steadfast love, covenant loyalty, mercy, kindness, faithfulness, grace, or combinations thereof. Multiple scholars treat the term as resistant to reduction to a single English equivalent.

## FLAG 4 — Romantic love is present but not structurally central

Exum notes that explicit romantic usage of ʾahav is comparatively rare and that reciprocal romantic love receives sustained treatment primarily in the *Song of Songs*. The broader Hebrew love vocabulary is not organized around romantic desire in the way many Greek discussions of erōs are.

## FLAG 5 — Concept/tradition boundaries leak

The Hebrew tradition contributes conceptual material that later becomes intertwined with Judeo-Christian agapē discourse. Any final comparison matrix should explicitly track lineage relationships rather than treating traditions as isolated.

## FLAG 6 — One tradition ≠ one definition

The Hebrew corpus does not support a single operational definition of love. At minimum, ʾahav and ḥesed function differently and should be represented as separate concepts in the matrix.

